===Etymology 2===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|bold|lang=enm}}, {{term|bald|lang=enm}}, {{term|beald|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|bald|lang=ang}}, {{term|beald||bold, brave, confident, strong, of good courage, presumptuous, impudent|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*balþaz||strong, bold}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*bhel-}}, {{m|ine-pro|*bhlē-||to bloat, swell, bubble}}. Cognate with {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|boud||bold, courageous, fearless|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|gmh|-}} {{term|balt||bold|lang=gmh}} (whence {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|bald||soon|lang=de}}), {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|båld||bold, dauntless|lang=sv}}. Perhaps related to Albanian {{term|ballë||forehead|lang=sq}} and Old Prussian {{term|balo||forehead|lang=prg}}. For semantic development compare Italian {{term|affrontare||to face, to deal with|lang=it}}, {{term|sfrontato||bold,daring|lang=it}}, both from Latin {{term|frons||forehead|lang=la}}.

